SIMPLE: postern
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Postern
<hw>Pos"tern</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>posterne</ets>, <ets>posterle</ets>, F. <ets>poterne</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>posterula</ets>, fr. <ets>posterus</ets> coming after. See
<er>Posterior</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Originally, a back door or
gate; a private entrance; hence, any small door or gate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He by a privy <qex>postern</qex> took his flight.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Out at the <qex>postern</qex>, by the abbey wall.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>A subterraneous passage
communicating between the parade and the main ditch, or between the
ditches and the interior of the outworks.</def>
<rj><au>Mahan.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Postern</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Postern
<hw>Pos"tern</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Back; being behind; private.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>postern</xex> door.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Postero</ent>⟦br⟧
